      <h2>The Process</h2>

      <h4 class="accent-green">I. The Fresh Cut</h4>
      <p>Sugarcane stalks are cut at dawn when ambient temperatures are coolest, preserving volatile aromatic compounds that define the final flavor.</p>

      <h4 class="accent-green">II. The Slow Boil</h4>
      <p>Fresh juice is reduced over a controlled flame for a minimum of 8 hours, gently coaxing caramelization without burning the delicate sugars.</p>

      <h4 class="accent-green">III. The Solar Finish</h4>
      <p>Concentrated syrup is poured into bamboo molds and dried under direct tropical sun, completing its final transformation into golden crystals.</p>

      <h2 class="accent-green">The Tasting Notes</h2>
      <p><strong class="accent-green">Aroma:</strong> Opening with toasted brown rice husk and warm molasses. Mid-palate reveals stewed golden raisins with a hint of five-spice. The finish carries a whisper of wood smoke from the cauldron fires below.</p>
      <p><strong class="accent-green">Culinary Versatility:</strong> Chefs prize Tinh Hoa Mía for Viennoiserie, where it awakens croissant caramelization and enhances butter. In savory applications, it provides a complex sweet axis behind Vietnamese caramelized pork, bringing 7 distinct flavor compounds.</p>

